With `allow_multiple_reduction`: if multiple of the token's top-k experts are on the SAME rank, their outputs are summed BEFORE transmission (at the source rank, during scaleup stage). So the receiver only gets one copy per source rank → buffer holds min(num_ranks, num_topk) copies. This reduces network traffic but adds a reduction step (less precise due to extra FP rounding... actually BF16 add is associative-ish but order matters for rounding).

Without: each top-k copy sent separately → buffer holds num_topk copies, single reduction at the end (most precise), but more traffic.

